def valid_move_combinations(pieces, positions):
    n = len(pieces)
    count = 0

    for i in range(n):
        for j in range(n):
            if i != j and not (pieces[i] == "bishop" and (positions[i][0] + positions[i][1]) % 2 != (positions[j][0] + positions[j][1]) % 2):
                count += 1

    return count
```

    The algorithm iterates over all pairs of pieces (not equal to each other) and checks if any of them can move towards the other without violating the rules of a bishop. If a pair passes this condition, it increments the count. In the end, it returns the total count of valid move combinations. It doesn't consider pieces other than bishops for blocking purposes, because rooks and queens can move in any direction and always be able to avoid a collision, while bishops are limited to squares with the same color as their own square.

